  "prompt": "Why do queen ants have wings? How often do queen ants reproduce other queen ants?",
  "response": "Let me provide some detailed information about queen ants and their wings:\n\nQueen Ant Wing Purpose:\n1. Wing function during mating flight\n- Queens use wings during a special mating ritual called \"nuptial flight\"\n- They fly to mate with male ants from other colonies\n- After mating, queens shed their wings and use the stored sperm to fertilize eggs for years\n\n2. Reproductive significance\n- Wings allow queens to travel and establish new colonies\n- They can fly to find suitable locations for starting a new ant colony\n- Wing-shedding occurs after successful mating and colony establishment\n\nQueen Ant Reproduction of New Queens:\n1. Frequency varies by species\n- Most ant species produce new queens once or twice per year\n- Typically during specific seasonal mating periods\n- Some species might produce new queens more or less frequently\n\n2. Reproduction method\n- Queens lay eggs that develop into potential new queen larvae\n- Only some larvae are fed special nutritional \"royal jelly\" to become queens\n- Environmental factors and colony needs influence queen production\n\n3. Factors influencing queen production\n- Colony size\n- Resource availability\n- Species-specific reproductive strategies\n- Environmental conditions\n\nThe exact details can vary significantly between different ant species.",
